Questions:
Represent the following functions of a function with the aid of chains made up of basic elementary functions:
(1) y = sin³ x; (2) y = ³√(1+x)²; (3) y = log tan x;
(4) y = sin³(2x + 1); (5) y = 5^((3x+1)²).

Answers:
(1) y = v³, v = sin x; (2) y = ³√v, v = u², u = x + 1;
(3) y = log v, v = tan x; (4) y = u³, u = sin v, v = 2x + 1;
(5) y = 5^u, u = v², v = 3x + 1.

Questions:
Write down the explicit expressions for y, given implicitly by the following equations:
(1) x² + y² = 1; (2) x²/a² - y²/b² = 1;
(3) x³ + y³ = a³;
(4) xy = C; (5) 2^xy = 5;
(6) log x + log (y + 1) = 4;
(7) 2^(x+y) (x² - 2) = x³ + 7;
(8) (1 + x) cos y - x² = 0.

Answers:
(1) x > 0; (2) x > -3; (3) x ≤ 5/2; (4) -∞ < x ≤ 0;
(5) the whole of the real axis except for the points x = ±1; (6) the whole of the real axis; (7) defined everywhere except for x = 0, x = -1, x = 1; (8) the whole of the real axis except for the points x = 1 and x = 2; (9) -1 ≤ x ≤ 1; (10) -∞ < x < 0 and 4 < x < ∞; (11) -∞ < x ≤ 1 and 3 ≤ x < ∞; the function is not defined in the interval (1, 3); (12) -∞ < x < 1 and 2 < x < ∞; the function is not defined in the interval [1, 2]; (13) -4 ≤ x ≤ 4;
(14) 1 ≤ x ≤ 3; (15) 0 ≤ x ≤ 1; (16) -3/2 ≤ x ≤ 5/2; (17) 0 ≤ x ≤ 1/2;
(18) -1 ≤ x ≤ 1; (19) -∞ < x < 0; (20) meaningless; (21) 1 ≤ x ≤ 4; (22) 2kπ < x < (2k + 1)π, where k is an integer;
(23) 2kπ ≤ x ≤ (2k + 1)π, where k is an integer; (24) 0 < x < 1 and 1 < x < ∞.

Questions:
Are the following functions identical?
(1) f(x) = x/x² and φ(x) = 1/x;
(2) f(x) = x²/x and φ(x) = x;
(3) f(x) = x and φ(x) = √x²;
(4) f(x) = log x² and φ(x) = 2 log x?

Suggest an example of a function specified analytically which is
(1) defined only in the interval -2 ≤ x ≤ 2;
(2) defined only in the interval -2 < x < 2 and is not defined at x = 0;
(3) defined everywhere except for x = 2, x = 3, x = 4.

Find the intervals in which the following functions are of constant sign or zero:
(1) y = 3x - 6; (2) y = x² - 5x + 6; (3) y = 2^(x-1);
(4) y = x³ - 3x² + 2x; (5) y = |x|.

Answers:
(1) y ≥ 0 for x ≥ 2; y < 0 for x < 2; y = 0 for x = 2;
(2) y > 0 for x < 2 and x > 3; y < 0 for 2 < x < 3; y = 0 for x₁ = 2 and x₂ = 3; (3) y > 0 in the interval (-∞, +∞), the function has no zeros; (4) y > 0 in the intervals (0, 1), (2, +∞); y < 0 in the intervals (-∞, 0) and (1, 2); y = 0 for x₁ = 0, x₂ = 1, x₃ = 2;
(5) y > 0 for x ≠ 0; y = 0 for x = 0.

