Find graphically the maxima and minima of the following linear rational functions in the stated intervals:
(1) y = 4/x, [1, 5]; (2) y = x/(2x-5), [-1, 2];
(3) y = (1-x)/(1+x), [0, 4].

Answers:
(1) for x = 1, y = 4 is the maximum value; for x = 5, y = 4/5 is the minimum value;
(2) for x = -1, y = 1/7 is the maximum value; for x = 2, y = -2 is the minimum value;
(3) for x = 0, y = 1 is the maximum value; for x = 4, y = -3/5 is the minimum value.

Questions:
126*. Draw the graph of the cubical parabola y = x³ and use the graph to find graphically the solutions of the equations:
(1) x³ + x - 4 = 0; (2) x³ - 3x² - x + 3 = 0;
(3) x³ - 6x² + 9x - 4 = 0;
(4) x³ + 3x² + 6x + 4 = 0.

Answers:
(1) x₁ ≈ 1.4, the remaining roots are imaginary; x₁ is the abscissa of the point of intersection of the graphs of the cubical and linear functions y = x³ and y = -x + 4.
(2) x₁ = 1, x₂ = -1, x₃ = 3; the substitution x = x' + a should be made, and a chosen so that the coefficient of x'² vanishes; further details as in (1);
(3) x₁ = 4, x₂ = x₃ = 1; see the hint on (2);
(4) x₁ = -1, the remaining roots are imaginary; see hint on (2).

